{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Sensor histidine kinase RcsC forms part of a phosphorelay signal transduction pathway with RcsD and RcsB. RcsC functions as a membrane-associated protein kinase that phosphorylates RcsD in response to environmental signals [[cite:PUB00074143]]. The phosphoryl group is then transferred to the response regulator RcsB. The system controls transcription of numerous genes. It was first identified by its role in the regulation of capsular polysaccharide or colanic acid synthesis [[cite:PUB00053678], [cite:PUB00074149], [cite:PUB00074143]]. Pathways regulated by the Rcs system include maintenance of cell wall integrity, cell division,motility, and virulence [[cite:PUB00074148], [cite:PUB00074270], [cite:PUB00074269]]. A novel signaling pathway that depends on RcsC, but independent of RcsD and RcsB, has also been described [[cite:PUB00074144]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR038388", "name" "RcsC, C-terminal domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"hamap" {"MF_00979" "Sensor histidine kinase RcsC [rcsC]"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Sensor histidine kinase RcsC", "short" "RcsC"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 117, "taxa" 1172, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1515, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1515, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1138}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of enzymes. It is primarily based on the recommendations of the Nomenclature Committee of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (IUBMB) and it describes each type of characterized enzyme for which an EC (Enzyme Commission) number has been provided.", "rank" 19, "ac